Let the shorter side have length $a$, so the longer side has length $b$.  Since the perimeter is $42$, $2a+2b=42$, or $a+b=21$.  Since the area is $108$, $ab=108$.  We want to solve for $a$.

The graph of $a + b = 21$ is a straight line, and the graph of $ab = 108$ is a hyperbola, but we only need one point of intersection.  The point $(12,9)$ lies on both graphs.  Therefore, the length of the shorter side is $\boxed{9}$ feet.

[asy]
import graph;

size(5cm);
real ticklen=3;
real tickspace=2;

real tick(real x) {

draw((0,x)--(-ticklen,x));
return x+tickspace;
}



tick(12);
tick(9);
draw(shift((0,0))*(21,0)--(0,0)--(0,13));
draw(shift((0,0))*(0,12)--(0,0)--(24,0));
fill((16,2)--(16,10)--(8,10)--(8,2)--cycle,gray(0.7));

label("$a$",(5,0),S);
label("$b$",(0,6),W);

draw(graph(x+21,(84-3*x)/4),Arrows(4));
draw(graph((432-3*x)/28,x),Arrows(4));
label("$ab=108$", (15,6.5));
label("$a+b=21$", (5,10));
[/asy]
